  e^{i \mathcal{E}_{(i,\hat{x})}  \left[m_x(i)-m_x(i-\hat{x})+m_y(i)-m_y(i-\hat{y})+2l_i)\right] } && \left | \{\mathcal{M}_{(i+\hat{\tau})}\} \right \rangle, \nonumber\\
&&
\end{eqnarray}
where $m_x(i), m_y(i), l_i $ are integer-valued variables on the coarse-grained lattice. Moreover, we define a vector $\tilde{m}_i=(m_x(i),m_y(i),\mathcal{M}_{(i,\tau)})$ and the lattice differentials are defined as, $\nabla=(\delta_1,\delta_2,\delta_{3})$ with $\delta_1 m_x(i)=m_x(i)-m_x(i-\hat{x}),\delta_2 m_y(i)=m_y(i)-m_y(i-\hat{y}), \delta_3\mathcal{M}_{i}=-\mathcal{M}_i+\mathcal{M}_{i+\hat{\tau}}$. and $\delta_2\mathcal{M}_{i}=\mathcal{M}_{(i+\hat{y},\tau)}-\mathcal{M}_{(i,\tau)}$. Using the above-defined terms,
the total partition function reads,
\begin{eqnarray}
{Z}_{\rm weak} & = & \sum_{\mathclap{\substack{\{\tilde{m}_i\}' \\ \{l_i\} }}} e^{ \sum_i \left[- \frac{m^2_x(i)}{2\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}}-\frac{m^2_y(i)}{4\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}}-2\Delta_\tau(\delta_2\mathcal{M}_{(i,\tau+1)})^2 -\frac{l^2_i}{2\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}} \right]} , \nonumber\\
&& \label{weakpart}
\end{eqnarray}
where the configuration $\{\tilde{m}_i\}'$ are the ones which satisfy the condition, $\nabla \cdot \tilde{m}_i = 2l_i$. We remember that the vector $\tilde{m}$ is defined on the coarse-grained lattice and is integer-valued. Using Poisson summation formula, we rewrite the partition function as,
\begin{eqnarray} \label{weak2}
{Z}_{\rm weak} &=& \sum_{J(i) \in \mathcal{Z},{l_i}}\int {d \tilde{M}} e^{ - \sum_i \left[ 2\Delta_\tau \tilde{M}^2_3 +\frac{\tilde{M}^2_1}{2\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}} + \frac{\tilde{M}^2_2}{4\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}} - \frac{l^2_i}{2\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}}\right]} \nonumber\\
    &\times& e^{ 2\pi i J(i) \cdot (\tilde{M}(i)- \tilde{M}_3(i+\hat{y})\hat{\tau}) },
\end{eqnarray}
where $\tilde{M}=(\tilde{M}_1,\tilde{M}_2,\tilde{M}_3)$ is a three-dimensional continuous vector and $J(i)=(J_1(i),J_2(i),J_3(i))$ is an integer-valued vector. The integration is carried over only for configurations obeying  $\nabla \cdot \tilde{M}(i) = 2l_i$. Next, we rescale the vector $\tilde{M}\rightarrow (\sqrt{1/2\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}^2}\tilde{M}_1,\sqrt{1/4\Delta_\tau \tilde{g}^2}\tilde{M}_2,\sqrt{2\Delta_\tau }\tilde{M}_3)$ and as a result the lattice differences are also appropriately scaled. We express the rescaled vectors as $\tilde{M}=\nabla \times A + \nabla\phi$ where $A$ is vector-valued and $\phi$ is a scalar, the constraint on configurations changed to $\nabla^2\phi=2l_i$. This condition is similar to the calculation of the potential due to the distribution of charges given by $l_i$ and the solution reads, $\phi_i=2\sum_j l_j/|i-j|$ for $|i-j|\gg 1$. Using similarity with the static electromagnetism, we infer that in Eq.\eqref{weak2}, there is no term coupling $A$ and $\phi$. As a result, we can group the
terms involving $\phi_i$ and $l_i$. This term is equivalent to the potential from static charge distributions, we will ignore it. The remaining partition function then contains only terms like $A$ in the exponent. Moreover, for simplicity, we only look into configurations for which the vector $J(i)$ is rotationless, i.e. $\nabla \times J=Q=0$. Then by comparing with the magnetic energy of electromagnetism, and carrying out the remaining integrals, we get,
\begin{eqnarray} \label{dipoleweak}
Z_{\rm weak} &=& \sum_{\{J_3\}} Z_{\rm pot}  e^{\sum_{i,j}J_3(i) V_{\rm dip}(|i-j|) J_3(j)  },
\end{eqnarray}
where the dipolar potential $V_{\rm dip}(|i-j|)=2V_{\rm C}(|i-j|)-V_{\rm C}(|i-j-\hat{y}|)V_{\rm C}(|i-j+\hat{y}|)$ with the Coulomb
potential $V_{\rm C}(|i-j|)=(1/\sqrt{2})\sum_{k} (4\Delta^2_\tau\tilde{g}^2\sin^2k_x/2 + 8\Delta^2_\tau\tilde{g}^2\sin^2k_y/2 + \sin^2k_\tau/2)^{-1/2}$. For $|i-j| \gg 1$, the dipolar potential has the typical scaling $V_{\rm dip}(|i-j|) \sim |i-j|^{-3}$.

\section{Appendix}

\subsection{Optical lattice potentials: }
 For the auxiliary species the super-lattice potential along $x$ direction is given by, $V^{a}_{\rm latt}=V^{a}_x \left [(1-s)\sin^2(\pi x/\lambda) + s \cos^2(2\pi x/\lambda)\right ]$, where $s$ is the tuning parameter to control the relative heights of the super-lattice. A standard $\sim\sin^2(\pi y/\lambda)$ potential is assumed along $y$-axis while in the third direction, we assume a tight trap limiting the auxiliary particles to the vicinity of $Oxy$-plane. Here $\lambda$ is typical optical laser wavelength. The bosonic $b$-atoms are trapped in a square lattice with lattice constant $\lambda/2$. In the third orthogonal direction bosons feel an elongated trap - compare the experimental setup in Ref. \cite{seng0}.  Such a scheme allows  to reach the regime of high boson fillings, namely: $\bar{n} \gg 1$. The superlattice potential makes possible the dimerized tunnelings of auxiliary particles as discussed in the main text (similar scheme has been implemented in \cite{Atala13}).

Let us now discuss the possible implementation of shaking procedures that lead to the effective Hamiltonian \eqref{hameff}.



\noindent{\it Scheme A: Shaking tunnelings and interactions}

We consider a standard tight-binding model in the lattice system described above with the Hamiltonian

\begin{eqnarray}
\label{ham}
{H_0} &=& -\sum_{{i},{\delta}}\left(J_a({i}{\delta}) \hat{a}^{\dagger}_{{i}} \hat{a}_{{i}+{\delta}} + h.c. \right)-J_b\sum_{{i},{\delta}} \left(\hat{b}^{\dagger}_{{i}} \hat{b}_{{i}+{\delta}} + h.c. \right)\nonumber \\
&+& U_{ab} \sum_{{i}} \hat{n}_{a{i}}\hat{n}_{b{i}}.
\end{eqnarray}

Comparing \eqref{ham} with \eqref{hameff} we see that the phase modulation of the $a$ species tunneling amplitude is missing in \eqref{ham}. To generate the effective Hamiltonian, \eqref{hameff} we add to $H_0$ periodically modulated (with frequency $\omega$) terms of the form

\begin{eqnarray}\label{shak_a}
H_{\rm sh} &=& - \cos\omega t \sum_{{i},{\delta}} \left(T_{{\delta}}\hat{a}^{\dagger}_{{i}} \hat{a}_{{i}+{\delta}} + h.c.\right)\nonumber\\
&+& U_{\rm sh}\sin\omega t \sum_{{i}} \hat{n}_{a{i}} \hat{n}_{b{i}},
\end{eqnarray}
where $T_{\bm{\delta}}$ is the shaken component of the tunneling and is non-zero only along the direction $\bm{\delta}=(0,1)$. $U_{\rm sh}$ is the strength of the inter-species interaction modulation.

The harmonic shaking of the tunnelings may be realized by appropriately periodically modulating the depth of the
optical lattices in the $y$ direction:

nexttext:
provided $K/\omega \gg 2{n}_{\sigma{i\delta}}$. Next we make the transformation: $\hat{a}_{{i}} \exp[i \pi \hat{n}_{b {i}}] \rightarrow \hat{a}_{{i}},
\hat{b}_{{i}} \exp[i \pi \hat{n}_{a {i}}] \rightarrow \hat{b}_{{i}} $.
Such a transformation maintains the commutation relations of the original operators.
As a result we obtain the Hamiltonian of the form given by \eqref{hameff} with modified, small $U_{ab}$, as well as renormalized $J_a({i}{\delta})$.

The effect of the asymptotic approximation of the Bessel function is that the number fluctuations become constrained by the shaking strength. This is in principle not a problem, specially for gauge group $\mathcal{Z}_N$ with $N \ll K/\omega$ as a result of the periodicity of the gauge group.

\subsection{Necessary properties of atomic species}

The proposed simulation of   the gauge Hamiltonian requires noninteracting $b$ bosons with large mean occupation per site $n_b$, assured through appropriate lattice arrangement (with $b$-bosons confined to tubes perpendicular to the $Oxy$ plane. Thus one has  to choose almost non-interacting atomic species e.g. using the  zero crossing scattering length around Feshbach resonance. One experimentally available possibility is $^{39}$K in the hyperfine states $|1,1\rangle$ and $^{133}$Cs in the hyperfine state $|3,3 \rangle$ \cite{patel}. The role of auxilary particles are carried out by Cesium atoms which are hardcore bosons due to strong interactions. The magnetic field is tuned to a zero crossing of the Potassium atoms which is around $350$ Gauss \cite{Roati, lysebo, modugno}. This range of magnetic field is also suitable due to the presence of Feshbach resonance in K-Cs interaction at $340$ Gauss. Thus a time-periodic inter-species interaction around $350$ Gauss can be used to generate oscillating inter-
species
interaction (as
required for shaking scheme \textbf{A}). Moreover, one can of course additionally control the scattering length using optical Feshbach resonances \cite{grimm}, especially for generating the time-periodic force. The use of optical Feshbach resonance can potentially allow for utilization  of a broader range of available ultracold atomic species.

Shaking scheme \textbf{B}, on the other hand is more versatile with respect to atomic species as no time modulation of interaction is necessary. The necessary condition is that the interspecies interactions, $U_{ab}$ are strong (again possible for the exemplary species discussed above close to the Feshbach resonance). Then adjusting the shaking frequency one can easily realise the resonant condition    $U_{ab}=2\omega$ and with sufficiently strong shaking reach the regime described by the desired Hamiltonian, Eq.~\ref{hameff}.

\subsection{Effect of gauge invariance breaking due to the contact interaction between bosons}
The next source of gauge invariance breaking process originates from the contact interaction between the bosons with $U_{\rm bb}\neq 0$. The onsite interaction between bosons can be recast as a summation over plaquettes with a locally gauge-invariant part and a locally gauge-breaking part. The gauge-breaking part is expressed as, $ H_{\rm U}=\frac{U_{\rm bb}}{4d} \sum_{i} {n}^2_{{i\delta}}$,
where $d$ is the number of nearest neighbors. By comparing with the plaquette operator we see that gauge breaking part acts as a small perturbation for $|U_{\rm bb}|/4d \ll 2K$. This gives a stringent constraint for the scattering length of the bosons in the regimes of few Bohr radii. Otherwise, the photons will acquire a mass $\propto U_{\rm bb}$ as well as longitudinal dynamics. 


